column2:
There are nearly two thousand streets and squares in Budapest named after people. These men and women may be real or fictitious, from the Middle Ages or recent history, and are Hungarians or foreigners. Attila Bátorfy and Eszter Galambosi of ATLO visualize all two-thousand streets, and discuss their findings in an accompanying article.

The charts show streets named after: (order read top-down and left-right)

  • Men (férfi) and women (nő)
  • Hungarian (magyar) or foreigners (külföldi)
  • Real (valós) and fictitious (fiktív)
  • Saints (Szentek)
  • Members of the Árpád dynasty (Honfoglalás és Árpád-ház)
  • Reformation and Dualism thinkers (Reformkor és dualizmus)
  • Contributors to Nyugat, an influential literary journal (Nyugat folyóirat)
  • Artists (Művész)
  • Clergy (Egyházi személy)

The final charts show the time period of each street name (Melyik korban élt?) and when the streets were last renovated (Átnevezett utcák 1989 és 2015 között).

In support of #VizForSocialGood and the United Nations Development Programme, Alexander Varlamov uses the Index for Risk Management (INFORM) to identify which countries in the Sahel region of Africa are most at risk for violent political crises. The INFORM model is based on three dimensions, each broken into two measures: the Hazards and Exposure dimension, including the "Human" and "Natural" measures; the Lack of Coping Capacity dimension, including the "Infrastructure" and "Institutional" measures; and the Vulnerability dimension, including the "Socio-economic" and "Vulnerable Groups" measures.

See more #VizForSocialGood submissions.

column2: This viz comes to us from sports contest winner, Ben Jones. This entry visualizes how golf players fared for each hole in the 2012 Masters tournament. You can select view an individual player's score, such as tournament champion, Bubba Watson.
column19: The dashboard below shows how golfers fared on each of Augusta National’s 18 holes over the course of the tournament

column2: Oracle CEO Larry Ellison may have just bought one of the Hawaiian islands, but he's not alone in the world of billionaires buying private islands. This viz by John Burn-Murdoch shows where are some islands that are privately owned, included some cool Google Earth images of what they look like.
column19: Private islands

column2: This viz by Marjorie Roswell visualizes the data behind the farm bill that's currently going through the US government. The heat map shows larger squares for programs that have a higher priority in the bill.

This viz by Craig Bloodworth takes BP's June 2012 edition of their Statistical Review of World Energy. He's made three dashboards, focusing on how the world consumes and produces oil, as well as each country's remaining reserves. The 'Consumption' dashboard is below. Unsurprisingly, the U.S. takes the #1 spot without much challenge.
column19: BP global energy statistics: the world's oil production, reserves and energy

column2: This sports viz was created by three University of Cincinnati students for a data visualization class. The Boston Celtics may have lost to the Heat, but they're still one of the most interesting teams in the NBA. Use this viz to see how the Celtics fared in one of their games against the New Jersey Nets, including where shots were made and which players scored the most points.
column19: NJ Nets vs BOS Celtics

column2: DataRemixed’s Ben Jones explores the woes of different professional sports teams and US cities, exposing which ones have gone the longest time without securing a championship.
column19: This interactive visualization shows every team and city in the MLB, NBA, NFL and NHL and how many seasons they have been waiting to win. Enjoy:
column23: Hurry up and Wait - Worst Sports Drought

column2: This viz takes a look at Wisconsin's milk industry. Milk production has steadily increased since the 1920s, but with a decreasing number of cows needed. In fact, the number of milk cows in the industry is steadily dropped since World War II.
column23: Wis. dairy herd size and milk production, 1924-2009

column2: Our nation's economy managed to grow in 2011, though the growth hasn't been easy. What industries and factors have contributed, and what has on average been a hindrance to that growth?

Who doesn't have some fond memory of a Billboard Top 40 song? Whether you remember growing up with popular songs in school, jamming to the radio or dancing in your living room, use this viz to explore all the major hits of the past few decades.
How hard is it to do business in Africa? It depends on which country, and on what metric you look at, according to this Global Post viz using World Bank data.
Much of our food today is imported from other countries, assuming it meets local standards. This viz looks at rejected food imports into Australia, where they come from and why they were rejected.
column19: Where failed food imports into Australia are coming from and what they are made up of.

column2: How common is your birthday? If you were born in the summertime, apparently very common. And if you were born around the holidays, you're probably pretty unique. Lots of theories abound; take a look yourself!
Individuals aren't the only ones contributing monetary funds to Congressional members--large corporations are too. Select a state to see the top 5 donating companies by contribution size.
Peter Aldhous takes us back in time with this viz of Japanese Earthquakes since 1900. Obviously, the island nation is no stranger to seismic activity.
column19: Japanese quake history

column2: Barry Ritholtz shows us the high proportion of US Aid that goes to the Middle East.
File this under the category of "Fascinating answers to questions I never asked". Namely, what is the condition of the US winter wheat crop?
column19: US Winter Wheat Condition

column2: Paul Kedrosky's viz below allows you to choose economic conditions, and then view the historical election data of incumbants who faced similar circumstances.
The Wall Street Journal made this viz to look into the detailed employment and income statistics kept by the BLS on thousands of jobs.
Robet Mundigl is an avid Tableau vizzer and mountain climber. Combining his two obsessions in this viz, you can see the highest peaks in the world from above.
column19: Visualize the 50 most prominent mountains on earth

column2: Presidents try to forecast unemployment, but are they actually successful? Ben Jones' viz shows us!
column19: This dashboard shows the track record of unemployment predictions by various U.S. presidents' Office of Management and Budget

column2: Alex Kerin shows us the history of every single tornado in the US since 1950. This is not just one visual story, but six! Click "States" below to start.
This beautiful creation is the product of thousands of bus journeys recorded by Transport for London. Mark Bulling downloaded the data and created the viz - nice work!
Here's a viz you don't see very often--a detailed story outlining all the stats of a still-unreleased computer game. Diablo fans, and all gamers, enjoy!
Ever wanted to see an interactive tide table? Chris Gerrard built his out in a flash... and with some impressive polish.
Tech IPOs have been under scrutiny this year but ended up leading the way in total capital raised during 2011.
This viz by MapLight tracks Super PAC donations, and it's getting our attention for a host of reasons: great use of a title image and a trick to get Hawaii and Alaska on the same map.
column19: So much from so few: The Origins of #SuperPAC Money. A visualization by @MapLight  #Election2012 #politics

column2: The Tim takes a look at King County, Washington home financing from 2000-2011.
The housing bubble never looked as good as in this Case-Shiller viz from Alex Kerin.
After the Japanese quake and subsequent nuclear power disaster, everyone is wondering where the nearest reactor is. This viz from Peter Aldhous shows us reactors worldwide.
Everyone knows sports stars are well paid, but the Guardian shows us the large disparity between different kinds of sports and even different leagues.

In an effort to understand the disparities in education both within countries and throughout the world, UNESCO created this view that displays the distribution of children ages 17-22 with less than 4 years of schooling.
column27: Education Poverty by Country and Dimension
